20@3@But whilst they were getting all ready, they heard the trampling of a horse at a distance, which so frightened them that they pushed their prisoner neck and shoulders together into a sack, and swung him up by a cord to the tree, where they left him dangling, and ran away.
23@7@As soon as the man in the sack saw him passing under the tree, he cried out, "Good morning! good morning to thee, my friend!"
